<district wordnetid="108552138" confidence="0.8">
<country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../635/16635.xml#xpointer(//*[./st=%22Khazar+coinage%22])">
Spillings horde</link></country>
</district>
</causal_agent>
</convert>
</location>
</administrative_district>
</person>
</physical_entity>
</region>
 and at other dig sites. He formulated the hypothesis that these coins, which were struck in imitation of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../036/804036.xml">
Caliphate</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../379/558379.xml">
dirhem</link>s and bore the inscription "Moses is the Prophet of God", were intended to commemorate the conversion of the Khazar kingdom to <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../624/15624.xml">
Judaism</link>, an event which Kovalev (and now other Khazar researchers, including <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../205/3540205.xml">
Kevin A. Brook</link>) dates to the year 838 CE. </p>

